The two broken and demoralised legions which had capitulated were sent back to Syria and replaced by the two famous legions of his former campaigns, to which were added that which should have j0ined Paetus from Moesia, and another now sent to him from Pannonia; the force being made up by its auxiliaries and the contingente of neighbouring prinoes to a strength of prob· ably from 4o,ooo to 5o,ooo men ⁶, and forming by far the strongest army in numbers and quality which had ever been despatched against Annenia.

We have again, as in former years, the same personal exaltation of Corbulo. The powers conferred on him are likened to those given in old time to Pompeius⁶ ; he is made to open out afresh the disused route of Lucullus ⁷, as if to recall the memory of that famous campaign in which a force, barely amounting to one third of that now following him, bad humbled the pride of the first Tigranes ⁸. Vologeses, who had offered conditions at Rome as avictor, sends to him as a petitiones and obtains from him an armistice⁸; the respect in which his name is held ¹⁰ is such as to make Tiridates accept without hesitation at his advice the terms of submission which had been treated as impossible in the embassy to Ner0¹¹3 after an exchange of courteous interviews, it is in bis presence that the dishonour associated with Rhandeia is obliterated on the same spot ¹² by the deposition before the eagles and the emperor’s effigy of the diadem which Tiridates bound himself no more to wear till he should have received it again at Rome from the hand of Nero ¹³; and itis with his dignified hospitality that the scene is closed ²⁴.
